UID:pmrcaa-pine-meadow-ranch-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260706
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:Deadline: PMRCAA Residency 2027: Process and Material (Pine Meadow 
 Ranch)
DESCRIPTION:Residency on a working 260-acre ranch in Sisters\, Central Oreg
 on\, near Bend and Redmond\, for artists\, ecological scientists and schol
 ars exploring connections to nature\, land conservation\, historic preserv
 ation\, agriculture and community building. THEME 2027: Process and Materi
 al - investigating the fundamentals of practice on a working ranch\; mater
 ials as memory and meaning\; cross-disciplinary work welcome including cer
 amics\, photography\, textiles\, arborology and beyond. STUDIOS: 9 studio 
 spaces adapted to different mediums (Tent Cabin\, Kiln Room\, Pickle Room\
 , Old Shop\, Tack Room\, two Hammond House studios\, Cooper's Penthouse wi
 th flatbed scanner/inkjet/GlowForge laser cutter\; Studio 6000 off-site fo
 r printmaking\; the Dairy Barn is unavailable in 2027). 24/7 access\; priv
 ate studio per resident plus shared Hammond House (private room with share
 d/private bathroom\, kitchen\, dining\, laundry). Wi-Fi in main spaces and
  select studios. The property is NOT ADA-accessible (historic site). Resid
 ents contribute via a community-engagement element (workshop\, artist talk
 \, or Studio Tour for the public\; participation in Studio Tour is require
 d). ELIGIBILITY: US-based applicants only\; emerging and established artis
 ts/scientists\; no specific educational qualifications\; collaborations su
 bmit one joint application. Alumni may re-apply every two years. COVID-19 
 vaccination required (or medical exemption discussed in advance)\; pets no
 t allowed\; ranch equipment and farm machinery off-limits without permissi
 on. TIMELINE: application opens 1 May 2026 (Slideroom)\; virtual info sess
 ion 15 May\; application closes 6 July 2026 at midnight PST\; finalist int
 erviews 12-14 August\; references due 24 August\; decisions announced Sept
 ember 2026. Selected by panel of external reviewers active in PMRCAA's mis
 sion areas.\n\nOrganisation: Pine Meadow Ranch Center for Arts & Agricultu
 re / The Roundhouse Foundation\nLocation: Pine Meadow Ranch\, Sisters\, Ce
 ntral Oregon\, United States\nAward: Free residency (no application or res
 idency fee). Stipend of $200 per week to offset living and travel expenses
 \; private studio + room in the shared Hammond House. Travel reimbursement
  up to $300 for qualifying residents based more than 1\,000 miles one-way 
 from the ranch (limited number\; trustee-approved\; paid post-residency). 
 Stipend is conditional on completing the full residency session.\nDuration
 : 2-week or 4-week residencies between March and mid-November 2027\; cohor
 ts of 2-4 residents share the Hammond House\n\nMore: https://roundhousefou
 ndation.org/pine-meadow-ranch/residencies?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://roundhousefoundation.org/pine-meadow-ranch/residencies?utm_sour
 ce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Pine Meadow Ranch\, Sisters\, Central Oregon\, United States
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:weho-artist-grant-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: WeHo Artist Grant 2027 (City of West Hollywood)
DESCRIPTION:Direct-to-individual artist grant from the City of West Hollywo
 od aimed at nurturing the long-term development of an artist's practice: r
 ealising work\, advancing conditions of creation\, and navigating the comp
 lexities of making art and making a career. The City's goal is to keep art
 ists in West Hollywood\, attract new artists\, and contribute to the city'
 s economic and social well-being. Awardees produce a 3-5 minute film descr
 ibing the project and its contribution to quality of life in WeHo\, and pr
 esent publicly at City Hall in November 2027. ELIGIBILITY (strict): legal 
 address must be in the City of West Hollywood (no exceptions\; proof of re
 sidency may be required)\; applicants must be registered on the West Holly
 wood Artists Registry\; previous WeHo Artist Grant recipients are NOT elig
 ible\; students cannot apply in their discipline of study\; cannot also be
  funded by another City Division or Department or co-sponsored by a Counci
 l office for the same project\; only one grant category per artist per cal
 endar year\; City elected/appointed officials\, employees and immediate fa
 mily ineligible. PROJECTS NOT FUNDED: fundraisers\, capital campaigns\, mu
 rals\, or religious-based programmes/events. REVIEW CRITERIA (40 points): 
 vision and clarity of project (10)\, impact of funding on the applicant an
 d WeHo community (10)\, portfolio (10)\, professional resume (10)\; peer-r
 eview panel forwards recommendations to the Arts and Cultural Affairs Comm
 ission. TIMELINE: deadline 3pm Wed 1 July 2026\; panel reviews August 2026
 \; ACAC approves September 2026\; notifications and mandatory orientation 
 November 2026\; earliest award of funds March 2027 (subject to contracting
  compliance). Submit two work samples (news clips do not count) plus a cle
 ar creative process and budget.\n\nOrganisation: City of West Hollywood\, 
 Arts Division\nLocation: West Hollywood\, California\, United States\nAwar
 d: $6\,000 per artist (total category pool of $30\,000/year\, so approxima
 tely 5 awards). Funds may be used in any capacity to fulfil the proposed p
 roject within the calendar year. No application fee.\nDuration: Calendar-y
 ear project\; mandatory public presentation at WeHo City Hall in November 
 2027 plus a 3-5 minute film summarising the project\n\nMore: https://form.
 jotform.com/260207043310136?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
URL:https://form.jotform.com/260207043310136?utm_source=artificialnouveaugr
 antdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:West Hollywood\, California\, United States
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:lanesboro-arts-bipoc-artist-residency-2026-2027@artificialnouveau.githu
 b.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260810
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260811
SUMMARY:Deadline: Lanesboro Arts BIPOC Artist Residency 2026-2027
DESCRIPTION:Residency for Minnesota-based BIPOC artists (Native American/Am
 erican Indian/Native Alaskan\, Asian\, Black/African American\, Hispanic/L
 atino/Chicano/Latinx\, Middle Eastern/North African\, Native Hawaiian/Paci
 fic Islander\, SWANA) and their families\, run by Lanesboro Arts in rural 
 southeastern MN. NO OUTPUT OR PRODUCT REQUIRED: the residency provides wha
 tever the artist needs (restoration\, family getaway\, connection to natur
 e\, access to rural community\, artistic practice) within the context of t
 he community\; only one community share-back event is required (workshop\,
  school visit\, small gathering\, or blog post\; arranged with Lanesboro A
 rts staff after selection). HOUSING: private bedroom + bath in either the 
 St. Mane Theatre Artist Residency Center (sleeps 1-4) or the Art Loft abov
 e the Gallery (sleeps 1-5)\; kitchenette/full kitchen\, studio space\, lau
 ndry\, Wi-Fi\; neither space is currently ADA-accessible. COHORT OPTION: s
 olo\, OR apply with a specific BIPOC artist collaborator\, OR apply open t
 o being matched with another BIPOC resident at the same time (both receive
  the stipend\; lodging split between St. Mane and the Art Loft). Spouses/p
 artners only get a stipend if they themselves are applying as artists in t
 he cohort model. SELECTION: lottery process (no traditional artistic-merit
  gatekeeping)\; 6-12 residents chosen depending on session lengths\; lotte
 ry is recorded and shared with applicants for transparency. ELIGIBILITY: B
 IPOC artists currently based in Minnesota. APPLY via the Lanesboro Arts we
 bsite. TIMELINE: initial deadline 11:59pm Monday 10 August 2026\; lottery 
 the week of 10 August 2026\; rolling applications thereafter if slots rema
 in\, until 1 April 2027 or until full. Lanesboro Liaison (staff or vetted 
 community member) optionally available for tours\, grocery delivery\, and 
 outdoor recreation (biking\, kayaking\, hiking\, state parks\, etc.).\n\nO
 rganisation: Lanesboro Arts\nLocation: Lanesboro\, Minnesota\, United Stat
 es\nAward: Weekly stipend of $1\,250 for food\, mileage and other costs wh
 ile in residence (half paid two weeks before residency\, half on the final
  day). Additional budget up to $500 per residency for art supplies if a cr
 eative project is pursued. Free private housing (St. Mane Theatre apartmen
 t or Art Loft above the gallery) plus access to studio space\, kitchen\, l
 aundry\, Wi-Fi\, and an optional Lanesboro Liaison for community/outdoor-r
 ecreation connections. No application fee.\nDuration: 1 or 2 weeks\; resid
 encies take place between September 2026 and April 2027\; 8 total weeks di
 stributed across 6-12 residents\n\nMore: https://lanesboroarts.org/bipoc-a
 rtist-residency/application/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_med
 ium=referral
URL:https://lanesboroarts.org/bipoc-artist-residency/application/?utm_sourc
 e=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Lanesboro\, Minnesota\, United States
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pioneer-works-visual-arts-music-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: Pioneer Works: 2027 Open Call – Visual Arts and Music R
 esidency (Brooklyn\, NY)
DESCRIPTION:Pioneer Works in Red Hook\, Brooklyn invites applications from 
 emerging visual artists and musicians for its 2027 residency cohort. 12 Vi
 sual Arts residents (5-month residency) and 12 Music residents (1-month re
 sidency) are selected each year through a two-phase jury process. WHAT IS 
 PROVIDED: free studio space\; access to facilities including risograph pri
 nter\, darkroom\, ceramics studio\, large-format printer\, 3D printers\, t
 hermobinder\, and laser cutter\; biweekly studio visits with curators\, ga
 llerists\, critics\, and artists\; free access to all public programmes at
  Pioneer Works\, including Second Sundays (monthly open studios and perfor
 mances). FINANCIAL AWARD: USD 5\,000 for Visual Arts residents\; USD 3\,00
 0 for Music residents (each comprising a USD 2\,500 honorarium plus USD 50
 0/month for the residency duration)\; applicants' choice on how to spend i
 t. Pioneer Works does not provide housing\, travel\, or visa sponsorship. 
 ELIGIBILITY: open locally\, nationally\, and internationally\; collectives
  may apply (resources shared)\; current students and programme alumni are 
 not eligible. REVIEW PROCESS: phase one is internal scoring on technical a
 bility\, uniqueness of vision\, and future potential (nontraditional caree
 r paths given special consideration)\; highest scorers advance to an exter
 nal jury of art professionals and alumni who assess diversity of demograph
 ics and media\, genuine studio need\, and fit with Pioneer Works' public-f
 acing culture. Jury convenes September 2026\; all applicants notified by l
 ate September. Supported by Dalio Philanthropies\, the Andy Warhol Foundat
 ion\, NYC Department of Cultural Affairs\, New York State Council on the A
 rts\, and the National Endowment for the Arts. APPLY: via Pioneer Works we
 bsite by 13 July 2026. Questions: residency@pioneerworks.org.\n\nOrganisat
 ion: Pioneer Works\nLocation: Pioneer Works\, Red Hook\, Brooklyn\, New Yo
 rk\, USA\nAward: Visual Arts: USD 5\,000 one-time award (USD 2\,500 honora
 rium + USD 500/month stipend for 5 months). Music: USD 3\,000 one-time awa
 rd (USD 2\,500 honorarium + USD 500/month stipend for 1 month). Free studi
 o space and facilities access. No housing or travel provided. No applicati
 on fee.\nDuration: Visual Arts: 5 months. Music: 1 month. Cohort begins af
 ter jury decisions in late September 2026.\n\nMore: https://pioneerworks.o
 rg/residency?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://pioneerworks.org/residency?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdes
 k&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Pioneer Works\, Red Hook\, Brooklyn\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wsw-artists-book-residency-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261115
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261116
SUMMARY:Deadline: WSW Artist's Book Residency Grant
DESCRIPTION:Women's Studio Workshop (WSW) offers an eight- to ten-week resi
 dency for artists to produce a limited-edition artist's book. Working inte
 nsively in WSW's studios in Rosendale\, NY\, selected artists print and bi
 nd their own books\; edition size must be between 50 and 100 copies. AMOUN
 T: $350/week stipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel
  within the Continental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. WSW
  provides technical advice\, training on new equipment\, techniques\, and 
 materials\, and production assistance. SALES CONTRACT: 20% of the edition 
 goes to the artist\; 20% (at least nine copies) stays with WSW for archiva
 l and institutional sales\; 60% goes to general distribution and sale. If 
 the artist sells through WSW\, WSW takes a 30% commission plus 20% for mar
 keting\; the artist receives a 50% commission\, paid annually around 30 Ju
 ne. WSW holds the right to sell distribution copies at a 20% discount to s
 tanding-order and repository institutions. WSW's books are held in over 45
 0 collections worldwide\, including the Library of Congress\, Yale Univers
 ity\, and Vassar College. An outside jury of artists and curators selects 
 recipients. INDIGENOUS ARTISTS: applicants may check the appropriate box o
 n the Submittable form to be considered for the BIMA Artist's Book Residen
 cy Grant for Indigenous Artists. APPLICATION MATERIALS (upload via Submitt
 able): current resume\; brief project description including media required
  (200-word maximum)\; materials budget form (Google Sheets\, Excel\, or PD
 F)\; up to ten images of recent work\; image script (title\, medium\, dime
 nsions\, date). MAILED MATERIALS (to WSW at the address below): a physical
  book mock-up demonstrating how the book will be bound or function\, actua
 l size\, with at least 1-2 fully realised spreads\; and the shipping form 
 (download and open the PDF locally). Mail to: Artist's Book Application\, 
 Women's Studio Workshop\, PO Box 489\, Rosendale\, NY 12472. Applications 
 open 1 August 2026\; deadline 15 November 2026\, 11:59pm EST\; notificatio
 n March 2027\; residency runs September through June\, one year after appl
 ication. Apply via Submittable at https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artis
 ts-book-residency-grant/.\n\nOrganisation: Women's Studio Workshop (WSW)\n
 Location: Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.\nAward: $350/week st
 ipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel within the Con
 tinental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. No application fee
 .\nDuration: 8-10 weeks\; residency runs September through June\, one year
  after application.\n\nMore: https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-bo
 ok-residency-grant/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=refer
 ral
URL:https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-book-residency-grant/?utm_so
 urce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ucross-fellowship-native-american-visual-artists-spring-2027@artificial
 nouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Ucross Fellowship for Native American Visual Artists: Spr
 ing 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Ucross Fellowship for Native American Visual Artists is a d
 edicated fellowship within Ucross Foundation's residency program\, offerin
 g fully funded time and space to make work on a working cattle ranch in th
 e foothills of Wyoming's Bighorn Mountains. The fellowship provides living
  accommodations\, meals\, and work space at no charge\, with no applicatio
 n fee. One Fellowship winner is selected per session\; all applicants also
  have the option of being considered for a general Ucross residency. ELIGI
 BILITY: open to Native American visual artists who are practicing contempo
 rary artists currently producing work in any visual medium\, including but
  not limited to painting\, drawing\, mixed media\, sculpture\, printmaking
 \, photography\, video\, animation\, performance art\, installation\, and 
 ceramics\; and who are enrolled members of a state-recognized or federally
 -recognized Tribe\, Pueblo\, Nation\, Native Community\, Political Entity\
 , or Alaskan Native Village. The work sample and project description are t
 he most significant features of the application. Unless the work is interd
 isciplinary\, applicants are encouraged to apply in a single primary disci
 pline and submit a work sample and project description emphasizing that di
 scipline. Work-sample requirements: VISUAL ARTWORK\, submit 10 images (JPE
 G format\, no PDFs) with file names including title and size\, plus a data
  sheet listing title\, medium\, size\, and year of completion for each ima
 ge\; FILM/VIDEO/ANIMATION/PERFORMANCE\, submit up to 3 video files (each u
 nder 8 minutes and smaller than 200 MB) or up to 3 Vimeo or YouTube links.
  The open call for the Spring 2027 session closes July 15\, 2026 (apply by
  11:59 p.m. MT). A separate Ucross Fellowship for Native American Writers 
 is also offered.\n\nOrganisation: Ucross Foundation\nLocation: Sheridan\, 
 Wyoming\, USA\nAward: Fully funded fellowship residency\; living accommoda
 tions\, meals\, and work space provided. No application fee.\nDuration: Sp
 ring session (February through early June 2027)\; residencies range from t
 wo to six weeks\n\nMore: https://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-progra
 m.html?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-program.html?utm_source=arti
 ficialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Sheridan\, Wyoming\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:princeton-hodder-fellowship-2027-2028@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260908
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260909
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Hodder Fellowship 2027-2028 (Princeton University)
DESCRIPTION:The Hodder Fellowship is given to artists and writers of except
 ional promise to pursue independent projects at Princeton University durin
 g the academic year. Potential Hodder Fellows are composers\, choreographe
 rs\, performance artists\, visual artists\, writers\, translators\, or oth
 er kinds of artists or humanists who have 'much more than ordinary intelle
 ctual and literary gifts'\; they are selected more 'for promise than for p
 erformance.' Given the strength of the applicant pool\, most successful Fe
 llows have published a first book or have similar achievements in their ow
 n fields\; the Hodder is designed to provide Fellows with the 'studious le
 isure' to undertake significant new work. Fellows spend an academic year a
 t Princeton with no formal teaching\, supported by a USD 93\,000 stipend f
 or the 10-month Visiting Fellow appointment. IMPORTANT: for this cycle\, a
 pplications are accepted only for the Program in Dance\, the Program in Th
 eater and Music Theater\, the Program in Visual Arts\, and the Department 
 of Music. Fellowships are not intended to fund work leading to an advanced
  degree\; one need not be a U.S. citizen to apply\; previous recipients of
  the Princeton Arts Fellowship are not eligible. To apply\, submit a resum
 e\, a 500-word project proposal\, and samples of your work (writing sample
 \, images\, video links to performances\, etc.). Applicants may apply for 
 the Hodder Fellowship only twice in a lifetime. The application cycle clos
 es 8 September 2026 at 11:59 p.m. EDT.\n\nOrganisation: Princeton Universi
 ty\, Lewis Center for the Arts\nLocation: Princeton\, New Jersey\, USA\; a
 cademic-year appointment as a Visiting Fellow (no U.S. citizenship require
 d)\nAward: USD 93\,000 stipend for the 10-month appointment as a Visiting 
 Fellow. No formal teaching is involved.\nDuration: One academic year (10-m
 onth appointment)\, 2027-2028\n\nMore: https://arts.princeton.edu/fellowsh
 ips/hodder-fellowship/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=re
 ferral
URL:https://arts.princeton.edu/fellowships/hodder-fellowship/?utm_source=ar
 tificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Princeton\, New Jersey\, USA\; academic-year appointment as a Visi
 ting Fellow (no U.S. citizenship required)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:accent-sisters-work-study-fellowship-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260801
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260802
SUMMARY:Deadline: Accent Sisters Work-Study Fellowship Program 2026
DESCRIPTION:Accent Sisters offers a work-study fellowship for individuals p
 assionate about literature\, visual arts\, and community engagement. The f
 ellowship provides hands-on experience in a bookstore and a hybrid event s
 pace where exhibitions\, book launches\, film screenings\, educational pro
 grams\, and other public programming take place. It is ideal for someone l
 ooking to build a career in cultural institutions\, independent bookstores
 \, or art galleries. Fellows work closely with both the bookstore and gall
 ery teams\, gaining skills in book curation\, exhibit planning\, marketing
 \, and community outreach\, while developing a personal project that merge
 s these disciplines. WHAT YOU GET: opportunities to work with writers\, ar
 tists\, and creators\; a chance to pitch projects\, events\, and programs 
 for a diverse community\; free passes to all in-person events and classes\
 ; fellow discounts\; a showcase of your personal project toward the end of
  the fellowship\; one-on-one mentorship with the Accent team\; and a USD 6
 00 stipend. Open to upcoming seniors\, upcoming second-year graduate stude
 nts\, and recent graduates of undergraduate/graduate programs. Four tracks
  are offered and applicants generally choose one: Program Coordination & C
 ommunity Engagement\; Curation & Administration\; Graphic Design & Digital
  Asset Management\; or Marketing & Business Development. The fellowship ru
 ns 20 August to 20 December 2026 (part-time\, 3 days per week\, on-site re
 quired). Applications are reviewed from 15 July to 1 August 2026.\n\nOrgan
 isation: Accent Sisters\nLocation: 89 5th Ave\, Suite 702\, New York\, NY 
 10003 (hybrid\; part-time\, 3 days/week\, on-site work required)\nAward: S
 tipend of USD 600 (paid in two installments)\, plus free passes to all in-
 person events and classes\, fellow discounts\, and one-on-one mentorship.\
 nDuration: 20 August to 20 December 2026\; part-time\, 3 days per week\n\n
 More: https://www.accentaccent.com/page/fellowship?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.accentaccent.com/page/fellowship?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:89 5th Ave\, Suite 702\, New York\, NY 10003 (hybrid\; part-time\,
  3 days/week\, on-site work required)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:gallery-penn-college-exhibitions-2027-28@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Gallery at Penn College: 2027-28 Call for Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:The Gallery at Penn College (Pennsylvania College of Technology
 \, Williamsport\, PA) invites artists to apply for solo\, two-person\, or 
 group exhibitions for its 2027-28 season. All entries are juried through a
  blind selection process by a gallery committee of faculty\, staff\, K-12 
 art educators\, and community artists\; review takes place during the Fall
  semester and artists receive notification in January. PROVIDED: housing\,
  meals\, a solo exhibition honorarium\, and a shipping and travel stipend.
  Promotional support includes an annual gallery catalog\, postcards\, pres
 s releases\, and web and social media. THE SPACE: the Gallery is 3\,000 sq
 uare feet with 82-250 running feet of linear wall space and an 11'4" ceili
 ng. All exhibitions are installed by Gallery staff\; site-specific install
 ations requiring artist installation need a planning document approved bef
 ore scheduling. Artists must have enough work for a solo exhibition unless
  applying for a two-person show. ENGAGEMENT: campus visits are an importan
 t part of programming (some exhibitions are scheduled without a visit). Pe
 nn College offers a B.S. in Graphic Design with foundation courses in draw
 ing\, 2D and 3D design\, visual literacy\, painting\, ceramics\, wood scul
 pture\, printmaking\, and computer graphics\; artists are encouraged to pr
 opose class-specific programs and optional community workshops. Visiting a
 rtists give a 20-30 minute gallery talk during the public reception (held 
 Tuesdays through Thursdays). TO APPLY: 10-15 digital images of work (JPG/J
 PEG only\, max 4 MB each)\, an image list with dimensions and medium\, a C
 V\, and an artist statement. For two-person or group proposals\, provide d
 etails in the comments\; for video work\, upload a PDF with video links an
 d details. Deadline 31 August 2026 for the 2027-28 season.\n\nOrganisation
 : The Gallery at Penn College (Pennsylvania College of Technology)\nLocati
 on: Williamsport\, Pennsylvania\, United States (campus of Pennsylvania Co
 llege of Technology). Williamsport Regional Airport connects to Washington
 -Dulles\; no other direct flights or trains.\nAward: Housing\, meals\, a s
 olo exhibition honorarium\, and a shipping and travel stipend are provided
 . No application fee.\nDuration: Exhibitions scheduled during the 2027-28 
 season. Jurying takes place in the Fall 2026 semester\; artists are notifi
 ed in January 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.pct.edu/gallery/exhibitions-entry
 -form?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.pct.edu/gallery/exhibitions-entry-form?utm_source=artificia
 lnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Williamsport\, Pennsylvania\, United States (campus of Pennsylvani
 a College of Technology). Williamsport Regional Airport connects to Washin
 gton-Dulles\; no other direct flights or trains.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:railyard-art-project-santa-fe-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260805
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260806
SUMMARY:Deadline: Railyard Art Project: Call for Temporary Public Art (Sant
 a Fe)
DESCRIPTION:The Railyard Art Project (RAP) facilitates temporary public art
  installations by established and emerging artists and arts collectives in
  Santa Fe's Railyard Park + Plaza. RAP is accepting proposals for temporar
 y public art installations and creative projects\; thanks to funding from 
 Santa Fe's Arts and Culture Commission\, two projects will be hosted betwe
 en October 2026 and June 2027\, each receiving a USD 3\,500 honorarium plu
 s marketing support and liability insurance. THEMES: the RAP Committee enc
 ourages collaboration across disciplines (art\, science\, history) and wel
 comes thoughtful\, challenging\, playful\, and edifying art in the context
  of social and cultural expression and environmental sustainability. Propo
 sed projects must physically withstand outdoor public display and engage t
 he community by responding to the natural and social landscape of the park
 . SELECTION CRITERIA: overall artistic merit\; context and familiarity wit
 h the proposed site\; practical viability\; and potential for community en
 gagement and cultural/educational enrichment. Artists should select an eli
 gible area of the park's open space and describe the project in detail\; p
 hotos or renderings may be uploaded with the application (a map of Railyar
 d Art Locations is linked from the program page). The RAP Committee\, made
  up of community members and Park + Plaza stakeholders\, selects and sched
 ules the exhibitions\; a formal in-person presentation may be requested de
 pending on complexity. CONDITIONS: the park operates under a Conservation 
 Easement\, so installations cannot be located on planted areas\, no stakin
 g of any kind is permitted (including during install/de-install)\, and not
 hing may be hung from trees. Artists lend artwork at their own risk (no pr
 otection against vandalism or weather damage\, and artists are responsible
  for repairs). Installs and de-installs must be coordinated in advance wit
 h the RAP Committee or Railyard Park Conservancy staff\, with a Committee 
 or staff member on site throughout. Application deadline 5 August 2026.\n\
 nOrganisation: Railyard Art Project (Railyard Park + Plaza)\nLocation: San
 ta Fe\, New Mexico\, United States (Railyard Park + Plaza\, City-owned pro
 perty under a Conservation Easement).\nAward: USD 3\,500 honorarium per pr
 oject (two projects selected)\, plus marketing support and liability insur
 ance. Funded by Santa Fe's Arts and Culture Commission. No application fee
 .\nDuration: Two projects hosted between October 2026 and June 2027.\n\nMo
 re: https://railyardpark.org/public-art-program/?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://railyardpark.org/public-art-program/?utm_source=artificialnouve
 augrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Santa Fe\, New Mexico\, United States (Railyard Park + Plaza\, Cit
 y-owned property under a Conservation Easement).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:target-margin-tmt-institute-fellowship-2026-27@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260713T104504Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260722
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260723
SUMMARY:Deadline: Target Margin Theater: TMT Institute Fellowship 2026-27
DESCRIPTION:Target Margin Theater invites applications for its next cohort 
 of TMT Institute Fellows for the 2026/2027 season. The Institute is a coho
 rt of artists who seek to radically disrupt and re-examine their existing 
 practice without any goal or expected result: pure experimentation with no
  product-oriented end goal. Fellows pursue no project\, no developmental s
 tage\, no deliverable\; misfires\, dead ends\, and bad ideas are considere
 d a fruitful part of the work. SUPPORT: TMT provides space\, material reso
 urces\, collaborators\, and a USD 2\,000 stipend. STRUCTURE: three short i
 ntensive sessions at Target Margin Theater in Brooklyn (5-8 November 2026\
 , 8-10 January 2027\, and 19-21 March 2027\, all day with some evening hou
 rs)\, monthly breakfasts at Junior's in Brooklyn (20 October\, 30 November
 \, 4 January\, 1 February\, 8 March\, 5 April\, 3 May)\, and occasional ex
 cursions. After the second intensive\, each Fellow commits to an explorati
 on pursued outside group gatherings\, supported by TMT resources. The seas
 on ends with an Open Studio weekend in June 2027 to share explorations wit
 h the community\; this is not a performance and should not be an audience-
 attended\, time-bounded show. WHO CAN APPLY: artists from any discipline w
 ithin or outside theater\, as well as production\, technical\, and adminis
 trative workers in the arts. Applicants must have an established\, existin
 g body of work and practice they are committed to changing\; do not apply 
 with a project. Recent graduates of training programs are unlikely to be a
 ppropriate candidates\; no formal education level or degree is required. S
 ELECTION: TMT staff and artistic community review applications and invite 
 a handful of candidates to interview\; all applicants are notified by Octo
 ber. Deadline: Wednesday 22 July 2026\, 11:59 pm EST.\n\nOrganisation: Tar
 get Margin Theater\nLocation: Brooklyn\, New York\, United States (Sunset 
 Park). Fellows must be available in person for intensives\, monthly breakf
 asts\, and excursions.\nAward: USD 2\,000 stipend\, plus space\, material 
 resources\, and collaborators to support each Fellow's experiments. No app
 lication fee.\nDuration: 2026-27 season: three intensive sessions in Brook
 lyn (5-8 November 2026\, 8-10 January 2027\, 19-21 March 2027)\, monthly b
 reakfasts October 2026 through May 2027\, and an Open Studio weekend in Ju
 ne 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.targetmargin.org/institute/?utm_source=artif
 icialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.targetmargin.org/institute/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugra
 ntdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Brooklyn\, New York\, United States (Sunset Park). Fellows must be
  available in person for intensives\, monthly breakfasts\, and excursions.
END:VEVENT
